               <p><normalised orig="Aunswere" auto="true">Answer</normalised>.<lb/>
<normalised orig="Euery" auto="true">Every</normalised> one ought to <normalised orig="bee" auto="true">be</normalised> most <normalised orig="carefull" auto="true">careful</normalised> of these two<lb/>
<normalised orig="poynts" auto="true">points</normalised>. First and <normalised orig="chiefely" auto="true">chiefly</normalised> <normalised orig="howe" auto="false">how</normalised> we can be <normalised orig="saued" auto="true">saved</normalised> in the<lb/>
day of <normalised orig="iudgement" auto="true">judgment</normalised>, before Gods <normalised orig="iudgement" auto="true">judgment</normalised> <normalised orig="seate" auto="true">seat</normalised>, and so<lb/>
come to life <normalised orig="euerlasting" auto="true">everlasting</normalised>. Secondly how to <normalised orig="liue" auto="true">live</normalised> according<lb/>
to Gods holy will during our life. In which two<lb/>
<normalised orig="poynts" auto="true">points</normalised> <normalised orig="wholy" auto="true">wholly</normalised> <normalised orig="standeth" auto="true">stands</normalised> the glory of God, so much as of<lb/>
man ought to be sought for.<lb/>
               </p>
            </sp>
            <sp who="a">
               <p><notvariant>Qu</notvariant>. <normalised orig="Howe" auto="false">How</normalised> can we know this, how we are discharged before<lb/>
Gods <normalised orig="iudgement" auto="true">judgment</normalised> <normalised orig="seate" auto="true">seat</normalised>?<lb/>
               </p>
            </sp>
